{
  "doc_id": "47674",
  "text": "Poor motor status (MRC power score=0-2) was found in a significantly greater number of acute hemiplegics than chronic hemiplegics. This is expected in view of the fact that gradual recovery of motor function (of varying degrees) often occurs with time in hemiplegic limbs. LHBT tendinosis was significantly more prevalent in hemiplegics with poor motor status than those with good motor status (MRC power score=3-5). This finding is in consonance with the results of researchers elsewhere [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] who reported that acute stroke patients with poor upper limb motor function were more vulnerable to soft tissue injuries during rehabilitation. These findings are, however, at variance with the results of other studies [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] that found no significant relationship between motor status and USS findings. This disparity may be due to differences in use, administration, and interpretation of different clinical scales for the assessment of motor function.",
